---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import ChatSim from "../../components/ChatSim.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "welcome")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        Claude is an <strong>AI assistant</strong>. Picture a very well-read, very patient colleague
        who's always available and never gets annoyed at follow-up questions. You type what you want;
        it types back. That's the whole product.
      </p>
      <p>What changes from one product to the next is the <strong>shape</strong> of "talking to Claude":</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Claude.ai</strong> — a chat website. Anywhere with a browser; drag in any file; no install.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude Code</strong> — a terminal CLI. Reads and edits your project files. The most powerful surface if you're a developer in a project folder.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude Cowork</strong> — a web dashboard. Hand off small tasks; review the diffs.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude Design</strong> — a canvas. Describe a screen; see it rendered.</li>
        <li><strong>Open-source agents</strong> (Hermes, OpenClaw, aider, ...) — third-party tools that wrap Claude for background work, multi-agent setups, or specialized workflows.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These overlap a lot. If you're a developer in a project, you'll reach for Claude Code most of the time —
        it subsumes what Claude.ai can do for you, and adds reading/writing files and running commands. The
        capabilities lesson next has an honest "when does each one win?" table.
      </p>

      <h2>How this tour works</h2>
      <p>Each lesson is built around a <strong>working imitation of the real product</strong>. You'll drive
      a fake claude.ai, a fake Claude Code terminal, a fake Cowork dashboard, and a fake Design canvas.
      The fakes are simple but faithful enough that the real things will feel familiar when you open them.</p>

      <p>Try the chat imitation now. Click a suggestion below to see it stream a reply (and, for some prompts, open an artifact panel).</p>

      <ChatSim
        prompts={["Hi", "Write a thank-you note", "Plan a 3-day Tokyo trip"]}
      />

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>One thing to know up front.</strong> AI assistants can sound confident and still be wrong.
        Treat Claude as a smart first draft, not a final answer — especially for facts, numbers, code, and anything safety-critical.
      </div>

      <h2>What you'll be able to do by the end</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Open the right Anthropic product for whichever task is in front of you.</li>
        <li>Drive each product confidently — the lessons mirror real UIs, so the muscle memory transfers.</li>
        <li>Build a real tool by the end of the tour (the capstone walks through three options).</li>
        <li>Understand the open-source agent ecosystem (Hermes, OpenClaw, aider) and set one up if you want to.</li>
      </ul>

      <Reveal q="Do I need to know how to code?">
        No. Claude.ai, Cowork, and Design are aimed at anyone who can type. Claude Code and the open-source agents are for people who already write code (or want to learn).
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Will I need accounts?">
        For the tour, no — everything here is a self-contained imitation in your browser. When you go to use the real products,
        you'll sign in at <code class="inline">claude.ai</code>. Open-source agents need an API key (covered in the agents track).
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
